After every run:
bashpython3 parse_fpd_run.py fpd_tune_data_20250419_142301.csv gains.json
This prints a summary and writes a _tracker_entry.json file next to the CSV. Then open the tracker, paste the JSON into the Import tab, check the preview (every gain, result, wave period, and amp reading auto-filled), and click Save.
What the script extracts automatically:

All gains from gains.json (preferred) or from the [GAIN CHANGE] log entries in the CSV itself as fallback
Roll and pitch RMS reduction %, both IMU RMS values
Peak disturbance and peak platform angles
Max motor amps for both axes
Median wave periods and cycle counts (same zero-crossing algorithm as your live plot)
FF and D term peak ERPM values
Loop Hz from the actual dt_ms column
Auto-generates the label from the timestamp in the filename
Guesses environment from the filename (wavetank/pool/wamv/sim)

The only thing you may want to edit manually after import is the label and any mid-run notes.



